<i>Sterling</i> (Old English <i>Stærling</i>), itself from the bird-name, whose use as a nickname may also be another source of the surname. Compare   Stare   2.","German: from Middle High German <i>sterlinc</i>, the name of a coin, hence probably a nickname for someone who paid that amount in rent."]},{"name":"Starlin","meanings":["English: altered form of   Starling  ."]}]},{"name":"Rose","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Ostensibly from the vocabulary word denoting the flower (Latin <i>rosa</i>). However, the name was in use throughout the Middle Ages, long before any of the other girls' names derived from flowers, which are generally of 19th-century origin. In part it may refer to the flower as a symbol of the Virgin Mary, but it seems more likely that it also has a Germanic origin, probably as a short form of various girls' names based on <i>hros</i> ‘horse’ or <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’. The Latinate form <i>Rohesia</i> is commonly found in documents of the Middle Ages. As well as being a name in its own right, it is currently used as a short form of   Rosemary   and, less often (because of their different pronunciation), of other names beginning <i>Ros-</i>, such as   Rosalind   and   Rosamund ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Rose Starling was born in 1499, in Dedham, Essex, England, United Kingdom. She married Robert Starlyng about 1514, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1562, in her hometown, at the age of 63."},"et":{"1499–1562":"1499–1562","1500–1537":"1500–1537","1520–1584":"1520–1584","1500":"1500","1499":"1499","Abt 1520":"umbes 1520","1520":"1520","1562":"1562","1584":"1584","Bef October 1537":"enne oktoobrit 1537","Abt 1514":"umbes 1514","1537":"1537","of England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Dedham, Essex, England":"Dedham, Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1499–1562"